<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Hesperocyparis</i> <i>macrocarpa</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>canariensis</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>halepensis</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>pinea</i> and/or <i>Pinus</i> <i>radiata</i> is dominant in the tree canopy with <i>Acacia</i> <i>cyclops</i> and <i>Eucalyptus</i> spp. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text"> Trees < 50 m; canopy is open to continuous. Shrub layer is sparse to continuous. Herbaceous layer is variable. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Pinus radiata</i> or <i>Hesperocyparis macrocarpa</i> > 50% relative cover in the tree canopy in ruderal or planted stands (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021).</li>
		
		<li>Introduced <i>Pinus </i>spp. or other conifers strongly dominant (> 75% relative cover) or co-dominant with other non-natives in the tree overstory (Verdone and Evens 2010).</li>
		
		<li>Planted or naturalized conifer species including <i>Hesperocyparis macrocarpa</i> and/or <i>Pinus radiata</i> > 50% relative cover in the tree canopy (Sikes et al 2021).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Planted as trees, groves, and windbreaks; naturalized in coastal areas.  </div>
</div>

        
