<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus radiata </i>is a fast-growing conifer that attains a height of 15-35 m and an age of 80-100 years. Trees produce cones at 5-10 years of age. Cones are generally serotinous and open after a fire or on hot days. Trees have intermediate shade tolerance. The species grows in maritime zones with summer fog (McDonald and Laacke 1990). <i>Pinus radiata </i>is a rare CNPS list 1B.1 plant in its natural mainland distribution of three discrete populations in central California (Monterey Peninsula, Santa Cruz/San Mateo, and San Luis Obispo Counties) where they grow on windy, foggy slopes and terraces in the coastal marine layer. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Hesperocyparis macrocarpa </i>is a coastal conifer that attains a height of 25 m. It is shaped or distorted by salt and wind blasting directly along the coastline, but a short distance inland, it is erect. Estimates of maximum plant age are 200-300 years (Esser 1994f). <i>Hesperocyparis macrocarpa </i>is easily killed by fire, and it typically regenerates from seed in serotinous cones as do other California cypresses. <i>H. macrocarpa </i>is capable of seedling establishment with or without crown fire because cones can open on warm days and shed seed without the aid of fire.  <i>H. macrocarpa </i>is a rare, CNPS list 1B.2 plant and only two native groves exist on the Monterey Peninsula. <br/>
<br/>
Though their natural habitats are few and fragmented, both <i>H. macrocarpa</i> and<i>P. radiata</i> have been widely planted along roads on the mainland of California where they regenerate and become 'naturalized' or ruderal. Also, both trees have been widely planted across the world because they can grow rapidly, and have been used as timber trees, for windbreaks, and as ornamental trees (Cope 1993f, Esser 1994f). Beyond these two trees, other non-native Mediterranean pines have been planted and are reproducing from seed, particularly in central and southern California, including <i>Pinus halepensis</i> and <i>P. pinea.</i> Naturalized stands of these conifers collectively interdigitate with maritime chaparral, coastal bluff scrub, and coastal prairies in California . </div>
</div>

    
	
	
