    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa, Ac-d, Af-l). Planted and naturalizing, non-native stands of cypress and pine in the section include <i>H. macrocarpa, P. pinea </i>and <i>P. radiata</i> (Jepson Flora Project 2021, Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-m). Planted and naturalizing stands of cypress and pine in the section include <i>H. macrocarpa </i>and <i>P. radiata.</i> Naturalized populations reach as far north as Humboldt and Del Norte Co. (Jepson Flora Project 2021), and stands occur in the Point Arena-Stornetta Unit of the California Coastal Monument in Mendocino Co. (Buck-Diaz et al. 2020) and generally in Sonoma Co. (Klein et al. 2015). In Point Reyes National Seashore and elsewhere in Marin Co., trees surround ranch houses and provide shelter from strong coastal winds. Some of these plantings have natural regeneration. Keeler-Wolf et al. (2003a) reported invading trees within stands of the <i>Baccharis pilularis </i>alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bb). Introduced stands of <i>Pinus radiata </i>are mapped in Sonoma Co. (Tukman Geospatial and Kass Green & Associates 2019).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-d, Bf-j). Planted and naturalizing, non-native stands of pines in the section include <i>P. canariensis, P. halepensis </i>and <i>P. pinea</i> (Jepson Flora Project 2021, Verdone and Evens 2010).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bd, Bf). Introduced pines appear to be naturalizing on slopes within chaparral (Jepson Flora Project 2021).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>H. macrocarpa </i>is highly susceptible to cypress canker, <i>Seiridium (Coryneum) cardinale, </i>which can kill this and related trees in the cypress family. It can be transferred by infected nursery stock or pruning tools (UC IPM 2017). <i>P. radiata </i>is highly susceptible to pine pitch canker, <i>Fusarium circinatum</i> (UC IPM 2017). Since several species of pine native to California are susceptible to pitch canker, the spread through the horticultural trade represents a threat to forests more generally (Camilli et al. 2013). To minimize damage, it is important to prevent movement of the pathogen to non-infested areas. </div>
</div>

    

    

